{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_013uSmvsPXGkHCKjoFsq3WfT","type":"tool_result","content":"   175→---\n   176→\n   177→## 4. Log Contents\n   178→\n   179→**Goal:** Capture all output (LLM conversations, script output, status messages) in a\n   180→unified log stream. Real-time streaming for active runs, archived files for completed runs.\n   181→\n   182→### Unified Log Stream\n   183→\n   184→The agent captures everything chronologically to `.cloche/output/full.log` with\n   185→structured entries:\n   186→\n   187→```\n   188→[2026-03-03T10:15:00Z] [status] step_started: build\n   189→[2026-03-03T10:15:01Z] [script] + npm run build\n   190→[2026-03-03T10:15:02Z] [script] Build successful\n   191→[2026-03-03T10:15:03Z] [status] step_completed: build -> done\n   192→[2026-03-03T10:15:04Z] [status] step_started: implement\n   193→[2026-03-03T10:15:05Z] [llm] Claude: I'll start by reading the relevant files...\n   194→[2026-03-03T10:15:06Z] [llm] Claude: [tool_use: Read file src/main.go]\n   195→```\n   196→\n   197→LLM output and script output are included inline in the unified stream. This is the\n   198→primary view for understanding what's happening.\n   199→\n   200→### Per-Step Files\n   201→\n   202→Additionally, per-step files are written for convenience:\n   203→- `.cloche/output/llm-<step>.log` — LLM conversation for agent steps\n   204→- `.cloche/output/<step>.log` — script output (existing behavior)\n   205→\n   206→### Real-Time Streaming\n   207→\n   208→For active runs, the daemon pipes container stdout to web clients via Server-Sent Events\n   209→(SSE). The run detail page gets a live log viewer. LLM and script output are visible\n   210→in real-time, not just status changes.\n   211→\n   212→CLI: `cloche logs <run-id> --follow` streams the unified log in real-time.\n   213→\n   214→### Post-Run Archival\n   215→\n   216→On completion, log files extracted to `.cloche/<run-id>/output/`. SQLite index stores:\n   217→run ID, step name, log file path, size, timestamps.\n   218→\n   219→### CLI Enhancements\n   220→\n   221→`cloche logs <run-id>` shows the full unified log.\n   222→`cloche logs <run-id> --step <name>` filters to a specific step.\n   223→`cloche logs <run-id> --follow` streams in real-time.\n   224→\n   225→---\n   226→\n   227→## 5. Container Deletion\n   228→\n   229→**Goal:** Keep failed containers for debugging. Show retained containers in the dashboard.\n   230→CLI command to delete them.\n   231→\n   232→### Retention Policy\n   233→\n   234→- Failed runs: container always kept (automatic).\n   235→- Successful runs: container auto-deleted (existing behavior).\n   236→- `--keep-container` flag preserved: keeps container regardless of outcome.\n   237→\n   238→### Container Tracking\n   239→\n   240→When a container is kept, record in SQLite: Docker container ID, run ID, project,\n   241→creation time, status. Updated when container is deleted.\n   242→\n   243→### CLI Command\n   244→\n   245→`cloche delete <container-or-run-id>` — accepts Docker container name/ID or run ID.\n   246→Calls daemon via gRPC to remove the container and update the store.\n   247→Single container at a time.\n   248→\n   249→### gRPC\n   250→\n   251→New RPC: `DeleteContainer(container_id)` — daemon calls `docker rm` and updates store.\n   252→\n   253→### Dashboard\n   254→\n   255→Run detail page shows whether container is still available. If so, shows \"Delete\n   256→container\" button. Project overview shows count of retained containers.\n   257→\n   258→---\n   259→\n   260→## Feature Dependencies\n   261→\n   262→The features have some natural ordering based on dependencies:\n   263→\n   264→1. **Container Deletion** — standalone, no dependencies on other features.\n   265→2. **Indicator Lights** — standalone domain logic, needed by Dashboard.\n   266→3. **Log Contents** — standalone, changes agent + daemon. Needed by Dashboard for log viewer.\n   267→4. **Web Dashboard** — depends on Indicator Lights and Log Contents for full functionality.\n   268→5. **Orchestrator** — depends on a working task tracker. Largest feature. Can be developed in parallel with 1-3. Includes the merge queue subsystem.\n   269→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"8530080f-5bbb-4b36-9913-140e127b35d2","uuid":"c31a34af-5183-4e71-89fc-bc253586a970","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/workspace/docs/plans/2026-03-03-next-features-design.md","content":"---\n\n## 4. Log Contents\n\n**Goal:** Capture all output (LLM conversations, script output, status messages) in a\nunified log stream. Real-time streaming for active runs, archived files for completed runs.\n\n### Unified Log Stream\n\nThe agent captures everything chronologically to `.cloche/output/full.log` with\nstructured entries:\n\n```\n[2026-03-03T10:15:00Z] [status] step_started: build\n[2026-03-03T10:15:01Z] [script] + npm run build\n[2026-03-03T10:15:02Z] [script] Build successful\n[2026-03-03T10:15:03Z] [status] step_completed: build -> done\n[2026-03-03T10:15:04Z] [status] step_started: implement\n[2026-03-03T10:15:05Z] [llm] Claude: I'll start by reading the relevant files...\n[2026-03-03T10:15:06Z] [llm] Claude: [tool_use: Read file src/main.go]\n```\n\nLLM output and script output are included inline in the unified stream. This is the\nprimary view for understanding what's happening.\n\n### Per-Step Files\n\nAdditionally, per-step files are written for convenience:\n- `.cloche/output/llm-<step>.log` — LLM conversation for agent steps\n- `.cloche/output/<step>.log` — script output (existing behavior)\n\n### Real-Time Streaming\n\nFor active runs, the daemon pipes container stdout to web clients via Server-Sent Events\n(SSE). The run detail page gets a live log viewer. LLM and script output are visible\nin real-time, not just status changes.\n\nCLI: `cloche logs <run-id> --follow` streams the unified log in real-time.\n\n### Post-Run Archival\n\nOn completion, log files extracted to `.cloche/<run-id>/output/`. SQLite index stores:\nrun ID, step name, log file path, size, timestamps.\n\n### CLI Enhancements\n\n`cloche logs <run-id>` shows the full unified log.\n`cloche logs <run-id> --step <name>` filters to a specific step.\n`cloche logs <run-id> --follow` streams in real-time.\n\n---\n\n## 5. Container Deletion\n\n**Goal:** Keep failed containers for debugging. Show retained containers in the dashboard.\nCLI command to delete them.\n\n### Retention Policy\n\n- Failed runs: container always kept (automatic).\n- Successful runs: container auto-deleted (existing behavior).\n- `--keep-container` flag preserved: keeps container regardless of outcome.\n\n### Container Tracking\n\nWhen a container is kept, record in SQLite: Docker container ID, run ID, project,\ncreation time, status. Updated when container is deleted.\n\n### CLI Command\n\n`cloche delete <container-or-run-id>` — accepts Docker container name/ID or run ID.\nCalls daemon via gRPC to remove the container and update the store.\nSingle container at a time.\n\n### gRPC\n\nNew RPC: `DeleteContainer(container_id)` — daemon calls `docker rm` and updates store.\n\n### Dashboard\n\nRun detail page shows whether container is still available. If so, shows \"Delete\ncontainer\" button. Project overview shows count of retained containers.\n\n---\n\n## Feature Dependencies\n\nThe features have some natural ordering based on dependencies:\n\n1. **Container Deletion** — standalone, no dependencies on other features.\n2. **Indicator Lights** — standalone domain logic, needed by Dashboard.\n3. **Log Contents** — standalone, changes agent + daemon. Needed by Dashboard for log viewer.\n4. **Web Dashboard** — depends on Indicator Lights and Log Contents for full functionality.\n5. **Orchestrator** — depends on a working task tracker. Largest feature. Can be developed in parallel with 1-3. Includes the merge queue subsystem.\n","numLines":95,"startLine":175,"totalLines":269}}}
